		<!-- Item text -->
		<div class="itemFullText">
			<p>Automation without drowning yourself in operative activities using modern technologies or misunderstood hell of various modules. Welcome to the OpenStack world.</p>
<h3>What is OpenStack?</h3>
<p>If you use virtualization, whether VMware vSphere, Microsoft Hyper-V, KVM or other, you need a tool to manage it. Something like this is just OpenStack. In my own words, I would characterize it as a middleware ecosystem between virtualization and services operated in a virtualized environment. It's not just the customer service itself but also the entire cloud computing infrastructure - servers, networks, data storage. With OpenStack, you will no longer have to worry about manually configuring VLAN networks across dozens of switches, and so on.</p>
<h3>When does OpenStack fit?</h3>
<p>If you run two servers running some virtual servers connected to two switches, you probably do not need OpenStack. You have the management tools that the technology will offer you. Also forget about OpenStack as a simple front-end tool for creating virtual servers. There are easier projects to provide you with this feature. One example is the CloudStack project, which is a personally simplified version of OpenStack. At the same time, it also provides a better environment for regular users. Alternatively, try Promox or use a solution that directly provides you with the virtualization you choose. However, if you run these servers, we can use OpenStack on them. The reason is simple - OpenStack is already running and we can put your "private cloud" under unified management and monitoring to get your servers started as our own.</p>
<p>If you run a larger cloud environment and automation is a key element in your infrastructure or if you choose to run a heterogeneous environment at the level of virtualization, switchow and storage solutions.</p>
<h3>OpenStack and Digmia</h3>
<p>The initial idea of ​​deploying OpenStack was a need to provide a virtualized environment for running Windows servers. For license reasons, this environment must be dedicated to Windows servers, and our rugged cloud-based cloud solution is built on KVM virtualization technology. Suddenly, we have a heterogeneous environment in which we do not move without automation, and we all want to hide under unified management. We have chosen Hyper-V for Windows servers. Subsequently, there were a few pre-infamous states that arose from lack of confidence in this technology, but Microsoft has gone a long way. If he wanted to be competitive in the field of hypervisors, he had to bring a sensible product. And the Hyper-V team in the current versions is already. Do you know that you do not have to install VirtualBox, VMware Player or similar apps on your Windows desktope? You have Hyper-V available on servers as well. Just in a few clicks.</p>
<h3>Getting Started with OpenStack</h3>
<p>We open openstack.org, download, install, go for a beer. If only. There will be a myriad of projects under OpenStack. You will find that you need some Neutron to make your network work. Then you will find that Neutron itself has countless modules from dhcp to bgp. Then you need a Nova compute engine. To store storage management some Cinder and ironically think over the provisioning of physical servers in the form of the Ironic project. A breakthrough will appear something on the horizon, which is to be a web clickable. Named the Horizon project, of course. I guess the gentlemen from OpenStack have a little to make your initial confusion about the name of the projects easier. But it will be necessary. Next, you will find that without the Keystone identity service you are not going anywhere and you are thinking about where to actually move. And you have to have a holimeter. You will have a toast to generate nice charts for leadership to see what this OpenStack actually does and why it's still not in production when your work report is longer than 500 scraped toilet paper.</p>
<h3>What does OpenStack do?</h3>
<p>At this point, it's time to tell what it's all about doing. Stay on the ground and avoid answering everything. You need a cool head and more managerial as a technical way to define what you expect from OpenStack and what you have to do. If you skip this step, you will literally drown yourself in the project overview on OpenStack. We have chosen this procedure. We are saddle and have agreed internally what we actually need OpenStack. Our motivation was not primarily to create a customer environment. However, we are not the seller of simple virtual servers in a mass scale. For our customers, we run complex applications from databases, load balancers, varnish, pacemaker clusters to web-based systems that are among the leading portals on the Slovak Internet. For this reason, our needs are directed internally for automation to simplify the management of our cloud environment. We want to know how to scale into the future and we do not want to limit it. The intention is to avoid errors in manual operations so that everything works reliably, easily, and accurately. And of course we want to have everything monitored by Zabbix.There's our new OpenStack environment. Under the hood with Hyper-V and KVM. The network divides Neutron on VXLANs and Cinder is responsible for connecting our storage servers. And that's just the beginning. In the next part of my blog, we will describe the different technologies and how we use them to offer you services under the Digmia - Expert Computing brand.</p>		</div>

		
